\cf2 3.2 Different Types of Blockchains (Public, Private, Consortium)\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Introduction\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Blockchains can be categorised into different types based on their accessibility, level of decentralisation, and purpose. The three main types are public, private, and consortium blockchains. Each type has its own characteristics, advantages, and use cases.\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 1. Public Blockchains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Definition:\cf3 \
\cf2 Open, decentralised networks where anyone can participate without permission.\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Key Characteristics:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Fully decentralised\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Transparent\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Anonymity or pseudonymity for users\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Incentivized participation (usually through cryptocurrency rewards)\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Advantages:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 High level of security due to large network of participants\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Censorship-resistant\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Truly decentralised decision-making\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Disadvantages:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Lower transaction speed\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Higher energy consumption (for Proof of Work systems)\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Limited privacy\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Examples:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Bitcoin\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Ethereum\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Litecoin\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Use Cases:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Cryptocurrencies\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Decentralised applications (DApps)\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Global, trustless systems\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 2. Private Blockchains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Definition:\cf3 \
\cf2 Permissioned networks operated by a single organisation, controlling who can participate.\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Key Characteristics:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Centralised control\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Limited access\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Higher degree of privacy\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Faster transactions and lower costs\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Advantages:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Greater control over the network\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Higher transaction speed and throughput\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 More privacy and data confidentiality\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Disadvantages:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Less decentralised\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Potentially less secure due to fewer nodes\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 May require trust in the controlling organisation\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Examples:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Hyperledger Fabric\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Corda\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Quorum\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Use Cases:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Supply chain management within a company\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Internal audit trails\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Streamlining business processes\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 3. Consortium Blockchains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Definition:\cf3 \
\cf2 Partially decentralised systems where a group of organisations govern the network.\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Key Characteristics:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Permissioned network\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Shared control among multiple organisations\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Balance between public and private blockchains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Advantages:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Increased efficiency compared to public blockchains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 More decentralised than private blockchains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Suitable for business-to-business (B2B) use cases\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Disadvantages:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 More complex governance\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Potential for collusion among consortium members\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Less open than public blockchains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Examples:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Energy Web Chain\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 IBM Food Trust\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 R3 Corda (when used by a consortium)\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Use Cases:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Inter-bank transactions\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Supply chain collaboration among multiple companies\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Shared industry platforms\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Comparison of Blockchain Types\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 1. Decentralisation\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Public: Highest\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Consortium: Medium\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Private: Lowest\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 2. Speed and Efficiency\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Public: Lowest\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Consortium: Medium\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Private: Highest\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 3. Transparency\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Public: Highest\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Consortium: Medium\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Private: Lowest\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 4. Scalability\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Public: Challenging\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Consortium: Easier\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Private: Easiest\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 5. Cost\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Public: Higher (due to consensus mechanisms like PoW)\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Consortium: Medium\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\'a0 \'95 Private: Lower\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Choosing the Right Type of Blockchain\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Factors to consider:\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Purpose of the blockchain\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Required level of decentralisation\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Privacy and data protection needs\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Scalability requirements\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Regulatory compliance\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Hybrid Approaches\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Combining elements of different blockchain types\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Example: Public main chain with private sidechains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Allows for customization based on specific needs\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Future Trends\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Increasing interoperability between different types of blockchains\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Growing adoption of consortium blockchains in industry-specific use cases\cf3 \
\cf2 \'95 Development of more flexible and customizable blockchain platforms\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Conclusion\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cf2 Understanding the different types of blockchains is crucial for choosing the right solution for specific use cases. While public blockchains offer the highest level of decentralization and security, private and consortium blockchains provide more control and efficiency for enterprise applications. As the technology evolves, we may see more hybrid approaches and increased interoperability between different types of blockchains.\cf3 \
\cf2 \'a0\cf3 \
\cell \lastrow\row

